FCC says:

When you create your variables in ':root' they will set the value of that variable for the whole page.

You can then over-write these variables by setting them again within a specific element.

The initial code:
<style>
  :root {
    --penguin-skin: gray;
    --penguin-belly: pink;
    --penguin-beak: orange;
  }

  body {
    background: var(--penguin-belly, #c6faf1);
  }

  .penguin {
    /* Only change code below this line */

    /* Only change code above this line */
    position: relative;
    margin: auto;
    display: block;
    margin-top: 5%;
    width: 300px;
    height: 300px;
  }

The task required me to change the value of '--penguin-belly' to 'white' in the 'penguin' class.

This is my code:
<style>
  :root {
    --penguin-skin: gray;
    --penguin-belly: pink;
    --penguin-beak: orange;
  }

  body {
    background: var(--penguin-belly, #c6faf1);
  }

  .penguin {
    /* Only change code below this line */
    --penguin-belly: white;
    /* Only change code above this line */
    position: relative;
    margin: auto;
    display: block;
    margin-top: 5%;
    width: 300px;
    height: 300px;
  }
  
The code change should reflect in the test environment where it was only applied to a specific area.
It is another example of granularity to your design.
